result.execSummary:
All charges against Justyn N Wooten in this case have been dismissed. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Justyn N Wooten is presumed innocent.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

10:33 AM; Case called for Hearing.  Defendant Justyn N Wooten in court, in custody at WCJ, with attorney Maura Ann Mcmahon.    District Attorney's Office Law Intern Jack Reider appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Atty. McMahon advises she has received the motion and reviewed it with her client.  Atty. McMahon notes that her client is not sure who is doing the contact the victim as he is not.  Atty. McMahon does not believe there is a basis for the protective order.  State presents statements and is asking the court to grant the motion for protective order.  For reasons placed on the record the Court will grant the State's motion for protective order with respect to Victim A.  Court to prepare and sign an order.  Court inquires how much time is needed for a plea and sentencing date.  Atty. McMahon is requesting a date at the end of August if possible.  Court adjourns for projected plea and sentecing.
